[2]
Date: 8 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Times of India 8 Jun 2003 01:47 AM [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/cms.dll/xml/uncomp/articleshow?msid=12162>

State wakes up after one more death
------------------------
One more baby died of the mystery disease at Lalgola on Saturday,
taking the official death toll to 21, even as another 200 children
were in serious condition despite the efforts of a team of doctors
working around the clock.
State health secretary Asim Barman said director of state health
services Prabhakar Chatterjee had rushed to Lalgola earlier in the
day to make an on-the-spot review of the situation. He has been asked
to submit a report to the government within a day or 2. Barman,
however, claimed that no new deaths had taken place.
The health secretary said 2 more medical teams, one each from the
School of Tropical Medicine and the National Institute of Cholera and
Enteric Diseases, had gone to the spot to support the ongoing
treatment of the babies fighting for life.
The fresh death was reported from the Natun Diya village. The
situation at Kadamtala, Natun Diyar, Kuchidanga, Raghunathpur and
Janardanpur is still serious.
"We have already checked about 3000 children. The cause of this
outbreak is still a mystery. We are trying our best to contain the
outbreak," said one of the doctors.
The villagers meanwhile face a Catch-22 situation, as all the doctors
were at the villages, with hardly anyone left at the hospitals to
take care of patients. The 4-member medical team from Krishnapur
rural hospital had to shuttle between 5 villages spread over 25 km.
[Byline: Aditya Ghosh]
