[3]
Date: 8 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Independent Bangladesh [edited]
<http://independent-bangladesh.com/news/jun/08/08062003mt.htm#A6>

Mysterious disease: No infection yet on Bangladesh side
--------------------------------
The mysterious disease which killed at least 32 children and attacked
more than 300 at the bordering villages of Lalgola thana of
Murshidabad district of West Bengal during the last 7 days may be
encephalitis, doctors in Rajshahi Medical College Hospital opined
this morning.
However, there is no report of infection spreading to the adjacent
bordering villages of Bangladeshi territory yet, RMCH sources said.
Dr Iqbal Bari, child specialist and Associate Professor of Rajshahi
Medical College Hospital, while talking to this correspondent, said
the 'mysterious' disease which spread all over Lalgola thana has the
symptoms of encephalitis and meningitis. He said that the number of
children admitted with symptoms of encephalitis or meningitis at RMCH
was normal and there was no patient with any abnormal symptoms.
Meanwhile, Dr Nazib Wadood, a child specialist and Director of
Al-Mahdi clinic in Rajshahi said that contact there was no report of
infection of the disease in Bangladeshi villages adjacent to Lalgola.
The Indian television, this morning, however, said medical teams have
been sent to the infected area, and the number of deaths from the
disease has risen to 32 from 30 during the last 24 hours, and the
number of those taken sick was over 300.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This latest series of newswire articles suggests that the etiology
of this outbreak is still unknown, with a variety of speculations
being ventured. In earlier postings there was a suggestion of
heat-related deaths, with the region undergoing a serious heat wave
over the past 2 weeks. A toxin has been proposed as a possible
etiology for the symptom complex described in the first posting. In
the above newswires there is mention of bronchopneumonia as a
diagnosis, and from the Bangladeshi newswire (the involved district
is a border district with Bangladesh) the possibility of encephalitis
or meningitis has been raised. The newswires mention involvement of
children less than 5 years of age; one of the postings submitted by
an infectious disease consultant in West Bengal did mention there
were 5 adult deaths, but further details were not given. More
details on the clinical presentation as well as the epidemiology of
this outbreak would be appreciated, in addition to results of
laboratory studies if available. - Mod.MPP]
